x .= .f(a);    compiles to     x = x.f(a);



str = .substring(1, .lenght() - 1);

compiles to

str = str.substring(1, str.length() - 1);



nested = is allowed, so the number of dots determines level, nesting order (not unnesting order).
.= is still allowed when this is used; it is the only assignment which does not create such a level.


